showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64884235"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64884235,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://fromnytosc.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/av/60x60/msnbc.jpg" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="true" /></a><a href="http://fromnytosc.newsvine.com/">fromnytosc</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64884235" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>The rate is irelevent compared to the cost of tuition. College costs are out of control. You can argue that football coaches make millions, but what programs pay for all the useless other sports on the campus.</p>
<p>When I went to college. many years ago, it costs $4,000 for 4 years in a private school. Another $10,000 for graduate school. I might add my degrees were in economics and finance, marketable skills.</p>
<p>I paid $60,000 20 years ago for my son to go to college. All toll, after 3 kids, I've spent well over $200,000 on college. What changed? Easy money, and no personal responsibility for repaying. Useless majors. And, the lack of a military draft</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64884235,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">1 vote</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64884235" title="Link to this comment">#1.2</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 7:15 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64890137"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64890137,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;The Mouzer&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=TheMouzerDFA29372-3A4B-252C-5E67-A1BA5957C69A.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/">The Mouzer</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64890137" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><blockquote>
<p>Easy money, and no personal responsibility for repaying. Useless majors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What exactly is a 'useless' major and how does one access whether or not a major is or isn't 'useful'?  And what do you mean there's no personal responsibility to pay back <strong>loans</strong>?  I think you are confusing <strong>grants </strong>w/ <strong>loans</strong>.  Grants you do not have to pay back, but you have to meet certain requirements in order to be given them.  Not every student qualifies for public grants.  You have to be at a certain income or be the first person in your family to attend college or have been an honor student in high school or something else in order to be given a grants.  Many grants also require that you meet a certain GPA in order to continue receiving them.  If your GPA drops then you are no longer given that money.  Federal loans work similarly <strong>except you have to pay them back- they are, afterall, loans</strong>.  You have to have a passing GPA (C average or above) in order to continue to qualify for federal loans.  Whether or not you qualify for federal loans depends on your family's income and whether or not your parents went to college.  If your parents went to college the amount you get in a public loan is less than if they did not.  If your family is of middle or upper income then the amount you get in a loan is significantly smaller than that of families who are lower income.  <strong>There are also rules on how you can spend your money and on what</strong>.  It's a federal crime, in fact, to spend student loan money on non-approved items.  You can and will have your public loan revoked if you spend it on items that are not approved <em>and </em>you could face jail time and significant fines as a result.</p>
<p>I should also point out that it's a federal crime to not pay back your public debt unless your public debt has been excused. Are you seriously admitting on a public forum that you and/or your children are violating federal law?  Dude that's pretty serious</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64890137,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">4 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64890137" title="Link to this comment">#1.3</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 10:34 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64890406"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64890406,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;meddlingmonk&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;MeddlingMonk&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://meddlingmonk.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=meddlingmonk23DE183B-C814-28CA-A930-EBE95749D42A.uncropped.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://meddlingmonk.newsvine.com/">MeddlingMonk</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64890406" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>Yes, tuition is a scandal and a horror. But I know a thing or two about student loan debt from a professional angle, and doubling the interest rate on the debt that some people are carrying would be an act of financial sadism. And letting the interest rate double would do nothing to lower tuition, so why even bring that into the question?</p>
<p>Your last paragraph is a patently nonsensical attempt to blame those with large student-loan debt for the size of their debt. Contrary to your 'oh-pity-poor-responsible-me' complaint, student-loan debt <em>must </em>be repaid, same as any other debt. I know for a fact that loan servicers are being required to reduce default rates. I also know that some people go into Chapter 7 or Chapter 13 bankruptcy over their debt, so bang goes that bleat. There <em>is </em>responsibility, and there <em>are</em> consequences for being unwilling or unable to meet them.</p>
<p>You should know that hose with the greatest amount of debt tend to people who went into medicine, or law. Do those fall under the heading of 'useless majors'? If not, there's another whinge down the crapper.</p>
<p>Finally, what the frak has the draft got to do with student-loan debt? Unless you are trying to make the case that the draft would allow more people benefit from the GI Bill (which wouldn't be that bad of an argument), then it seems like you have simply resorted to padding.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64890406,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;meddlingmonk&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">2 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64890406" title="Link to this comment">#1.4</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 10:45 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><img class="replybutton" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_reply_mini.gif" width="35" height="12" alt="Reply" /></div><div class="commentcontainer"><span></span></div></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody " id="c64874690"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64874690,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;The Mouzer&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=TheMouzerDFA29372-3A4B-252C-5E67-A1BA5957C69A.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/">The Mouzer</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64874690" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>So let me get this straight.  We <em>could </em>pass the Buffet rule and that would bring in about enough revenue to cover the student loans.</p>
<p>....Or we can spend that money giving tax cuts</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Mitt Romney has said he intends to <a href="../../03/20/10775061-how-not-to-compete-for-the-youth-vote">dramatically scale back</a> the federal role in helping students go to college.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yes because that will help us <em>totally </em>bring jobs back to the US.  Do these people ever think things through?!</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64874690,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">3 votes</div></li></ul></div><img class="replybutton" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_reply_mini.gif" width="35" height="12" alt="Reply" /><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64874690" title="Link to this comment">#2</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 3:57 PM EDT</span><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64875618"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64875618,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;crackheadawards&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;Crackhead Awards&quot;}"></div><a name="star2"></a><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="#star3" class="noborder star"><img src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_star.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Jump To Next Highly Rated Comment" /></a><a href="http://crackheadawards.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=crackheadawards0FB1C990-46E1-7BC7-5FED-F27987334B67.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://crackheadawards.newsvine.com/">Crackhead Awards</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64875618" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>I believe Rome had a similar experience.</p>
<p>No ... wait ... Rome collapsed because the slaves revolted against the wealthy.</p>
<p>I believe France had a similar experience.</p>
<p>No ... wait ... the King and Queen were beheaded when the poor revolted.</p>
<p>Looks like a pattern to me.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64875618,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;crackheadawards&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">6 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64875618" title="Link to this comment">#2.1</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 4:11 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64878688"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64878688,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;grumpyliberalbastard&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;grumpyliberalbastard&quot;}"></div><a name="star3"></a><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="#star4" class="noborder star"><img src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_star.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Jump To Next Highly Rated Comment" /></a><a href="http://grumpyliberalbastard.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=grumpyliberalbastard96BE2864-CD76-3C4E-F5F3-E77C931ABA92.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://grumpyliberalbastard.newsvine.com/">grumpyliberalbastard</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64878688" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>Sadly, the violent people in this society also tend to be the ones stupid enough to buy the GOP's line of bullcrap.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64878688,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;grumpyliberalbastard&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">7 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64878688" title="Link to this comment">#2.2</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 4:52 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><img class="replybutton" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_reply_mini.gif" width="35" height="12" alt="Reply" /></div><div class="commentcontainer"><span></span></div></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody " id="c64875093"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64875093,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;crackheadawards&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;Crackhead Awards&quot;}"></div><a name="star4"></a><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="#star5" class="noborder star"><img src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_star.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Jump To Next Highly Rated Comment" /></a><a href="http://crackheadawards.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=crackheadawards0FB1C990-46E1-7BC7-5FED-F27987334B67.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://crackheadawards.newsvine.com/">Crackhead Awards</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64875093" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>Pell Grants and the GI Bill are the only thing besides the US Mint that runs a profit.</p>
<p>It costs about $20,000 for a bachelors degree from a state college.</p>
<p>College increases income from about $13/hour to about $25/hour.</p>
<p>This doubles income, and the corresponding tax increase is about $300,000 over a lifetime.</p>
<p>That is called profit.</p>
<p>Over 1,000% return on investment.</p>
<p>A college education prevents incarceration, so this reduces government spending (a hot topic with the GOP).</p>
<p>You have to be a <em><strong>flaming idiot</strong></em> to fail to recognize that the US economy began to dominate the world after the Pell Grant and GI BIll programs began.</p>
<p>Stafford Loans prop up the Pell Grant and GI Bill program.</p>
<p>These loans could be cancelled without risk after graduation from a low-cost public college because additional tax revenue will make up for the loss.</p>
<p>Even with $140,000 average cost per student, education still runs a profit if you provide free education.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64875093,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;crackheadawards&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">5 votes</div></li></ul></div><img class="replybutton" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_reply_mini.gif" width="35" height="12" alt="Reply" /><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64875093" title="Link to this comment">#3</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 4:03 PM EDT</span><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64877987"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64877987,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;mikepaganucci&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;Mike Paganucci&quot;}"></div><a name="star5"></a><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="#star6" class="noborder star"><img src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/b_star.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Jump To Next Highly Rated Comment" /></a><a href="http://mikepaganucci.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=MikePaganucci4F1A3621-BC3D-8B26-966E-765BB6FB82FC.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://mikepaganucci.newsvine.com/">Mike Paganucci</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64877987" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>The antipathy toward education comes from the groups of older people who have already received an education and their children are out of school. Now they believe that they should not have to pay for the education for other people and their children. That is part of the reason why people support the Republicans. A second reason is that some people believe the children are being indoctrinated with liberal/progressive/socialist/communist philosophy which they see as one and the same.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64877987,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;mikepaganucci&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">5 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64877987" title="Link to this comment">#3.1</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 4:32 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64879149"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64879149,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fb-paulsc2&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;Paul S. Campbell&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://fb-paulsc2.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=fb-paulsc22A1B2BE7-7D1A-0DDB-5307-F706759E0B19.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://fb-paulsc2.newsvine.com/">Paul S. Campbell</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64879149" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>You are trying to use logic and facts to make your case. The problem here is that those opposed to college loans and grants believe that a college education is a waste of time that should be spent on the job. You see they either had too poor of a GPA to get in or they did not want to knuckle down and learn when they could pull wrenches and drink beer instead. They see college as evil and all professors as far left radicals. They would have loved being raised in the USSR where their future would have been planned for them by the state. There they would have been told early that they were too ignorant to become engineers so they must go to a vocational high and become laborers.</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64879149,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fb-paulsc2&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">2 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64879149" title="Link to this comment">#3.2</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 5:03 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64886998"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64886998,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://fromnytosc.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/av/60x60/msnbc.jpg" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="true" /></a><a href="http://fromnytosc.newsvine.com/">fromnytosc</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64886998" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><p>You make absolutely no sense. On behalf of my older generation, we see the value of a college education. We also see  the value in  blue collar work. The choice of which to persue is a personal one. But, we don't see college as an entitlement to be paid for by the tax payers.</p>
<p>I just question why the cost of college has increased so much since the 60's, far outpacing inflation. I also question the expansion in the number of college programs which offer little opportunity for expansive job offerings. Why major in puppeteering?</p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64886998,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;fromnytosc&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64886998" title="Link to this comment">#3.3</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 8:55 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64889346"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64889346,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;The Mouzer&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=TheMouzerDFA29372-3A4B-252C-5E67-A1BA5957C69A.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://themouzer.newsvine.com/">The Mouzer</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64889346" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><blockquote>
<p>But, we don't see college as an entitlement to be paid for by the tax payers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Oh good lord.  These are <strong>loans </strong>given out to a person.  The only difference between a government loan and private business loan is that the government is able to provide you w/ an artificially lower rate.  You <strong>must </strong>pay back your FAFSA and other loans over time.  They will <strong>only </strong>waive that debt if it's been more than 20 years since you took out the loan and more than 75% of your tuition has been paid off.</p>
<p>Beyond this <strong>it costs the taxpayers more money to not pay for college</strong>.  This is why the government pays for student loans and grants in the first place.  People who earn a degree make more money and therefore pay more in taxes.  This, then, <strong>reduces </strong>the debt.  It does not increase it.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I just question why the cost of college has increased so much since the  60's, far outpacing inflation. I also question the expansion in the  number of college programs which offer little opportunity for expansive  job offerings. Why major in puppeteering?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The purpose of a college degree is not singularly focused on that of getting a person a job, although this is the majority reason for why people attend school.  College is a higher learning institution which means it's primary focus is on educating a person.  Jobs, at least hypothetically, come about as a result of the critical thinking skills a person gains from school.</p>
<p>FTR I'm not sure about a school that gives you the major of puppeteering.  I am sure that there are schools that give you the major of <em>acting </em>or <em>theater</em> and included in that may be an emphasis on puppeteering...although I've never encountered such a thing.  That seems like something you'd get at an apprenticeship school or at a community college for non-credit.  But even so you're making an assumption here that a person could not turn that into a profession.  While certainly it would be more difficult presumably someone going into the major of puppeteering would be well aware of his/her employment opportunities, the struggles inherent w/in, and would be making the decision on the basis of such.</p>
<p>For the record there is no guarantee that any college degree will land a person a job.  I know a person who graduated at the top of his class in the Air Force Academy who went on to become a registered Physical Therapist w/ the Air Force.  He got his PT certification for the state of CO when his commissionship came up, but he could not get a job.  So he now is a landscaper.  I know another individual who is a close friend of mine who has an undergraduates degree in Computer Science from NYU and a graduate's degree in mathematics from MIT.  He to this day has not been able to find a job w/ any industry...luckily for him his father owns a small computer service repair company and that's where he works now.  I also know a person who has a law degree and still cannot find work. </p></p></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_MiniToolbox"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64889346,&quot;threadId&quot;:&quot;3399606&quot;,&quot;contentId&quot;:&quot;11311001&quot;,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;themouzer&quot;}"></div><ul class="list"><li class="box votes"><div class="label">3 votes</div></li></ul></div><span class="commentdate"><a href="#c64889346" title="Link to this comment">#3.4</a> - Fri Apr 20, 2012 10:13 PM EDT</span></div></div></div><div class="vine-p p-comment_Comment showAvatars commentbody child " id="c64890648"><div class="printerData hide" data-printer="{&quot;commentId&quot;:64890648,&quot;authorDomain&quot;:&quot;meddlingmonk&quot;,&quot;authorDisplayName&quot;:&quot;MeddlingMonk&quot;}"></div><div class="c_author"><div class="normal"><a href="http://meddlingmonk.newsvine.com/"><img class="comment_author_avatar" src="http://www.cdn.newsvine.com/_vine/images/_/blank.gif" data-avatar_src="http://m.static.newsvine.com/servista/imagesizer?file=meddlingmonk23DE183B-C814-28CA-A930-EBE95749D42A.uncropped.jpg&width=60" width="35" height="35" alt="Comment author avatar" data-is_default_avatar="false" /></a><a href="http://meddlingmonk.newsvine.com/">MeddlingMonk</a></div></div><div id="commentText_64890648" class="c_text"><div class="normal"><div class="commentSource"><blockquote>
<p>But, we don't see college as an entitlement to be paid for by the tax payers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Then, oh happy day! What you disapprove of <em>doesn't freaking exist!!!</em></p>
